2020-10-02T09:08:15.643974+00:00 2020-12-30T16:00:00+00:00 20000 false quezon-city-local-government Quezon City is a vast and teeming city with a steadily increasing income and occupation of one-third of Metro Manila’s total land area. It now serves as the Philippines’ government center with the legislature and other important government offices located in its area. All of these are reminiscent of the same noble dream that brought forth the creation of the City.

Quezon City is situated on the northeast portion of Metro Manila. It is bounded on the north by Caloocan City and San Jose del Monte City in Bulacan Province, on the east by San Mateo and Marikina, on the south by Pasig and Mandaluyong, San Juan and Manila, and on the west by Valenzuela, Caloocan, and Manila. Its northeastern and eastern boundaries are defined by the Novaliches Watershed and the Marikina River. With an area of 16,112.58 hectares (based on 1995 GIS graphical plot), it is the largest among the sixteen (16) cities and one (1) municipality in the region and is almost one-fourth the size of Metro Manila.

VISION

The Quezon City Government envisions itself to be a model of effective governance and responsible leadership, working in partnership with the citizenry in building a Quality Community.

MISSION

To provide quality service which will make Quezon City an ideal community where people live, work and do business in a hospitable, progressive & peaceful environment.

In addition, it was made the authorized distributor of the following brands:

• Pioneer Balloons from the U.S.A. in 1995
• BIC Stationery products from France in 2001; BIC Lighters and Shavers (exclusive distributorship)
• Everts Balloons from Malaysia in 2003
• Martha Stewart Crafts
• Scentco
• Disney Art Attack in 2012 (Licensee)
• Crayola (Licensee)

The company was the first to introduce the scrapbooking hobby in the Philippines, creating the brand Craft Easy, formerly known as All About Scrapbooking.

Other of its locally-created brands include:

• Celebration Balloons
• Wrapsody - a line of high-end quality gift wrap paper with special effects
• Wrap 'Em Up – ribbons and quick gift wrapping ideas
• Photofun photo albums

THE STORY OF THE HALLMARK BRAND AND FILSTAR, THE COMPANY, IN THE PHILIPPINES

The beginnings of Hallmark in the Philippines had its share of twists and charm. In 1969, people from Kansas City, U.S.A., home of the Hallmark headquarters, came to the Philippines looking for a local licensee. It was in National Book Store (NBS) that Hallmark discovered the qualities they too valued: the premium placed on excellence and the right attitude towards growth. These were the same qualities which the founder of NBS, Mrs. Socorro C. Ramos, valued.

It was a Good Friday when Mrs. Ramos was approached by Hallmark U.S.A. Thereafter, she went to Kansas City to arrange the deal and successfully came back with the license to manufacture and distribute Hallmark in the Philippines. It was on her kitchen table that the very first cards were planned. This was in 1973, the start of the Hallmark- NBS partnership. The next year, Hallmark cards made their appearance on the racks of National Book Store.

What followed were years of astounding growth and excellence. In product lines, from Christmas to everyday themes, more greeting cards and other excellent products have been added on each year to establish a full line of quality Hallmark merchandise.

Today, Filstar distributes to 1,000 outlets nationwide and has evolved to be a distributor of not just Hallmark, but of other products that supplement and enhance the personal expressions industry. The successful introduction of the All About Scrapbooking brand spearheaded the art of scrapbooking in the Philippines. It is now the top of mind brand of scrapbooking enthusiasts and hobbyists.		 22812 Retail Industry https://rec-data.kalibrr.com/logos/HE3KW56HQ9WRQHMYHZ4Y-5a2118fe.png Filstar Distributors Corporation true true filstar-distributors-corporation Filstar Distributors Corporation maintains the prestige of being the exclusive licensee of Hallmark Cards in the Philippines since 1974. It now serves as the Philippines’ government center with the legislature and other important government offices located in its area. All of these are reminiscent of the same noble dream that brought forth the creation of the City.

Quezon City is situated on the northeast portion of Metro Manila. It is bounded on the north by Caloocan City and San Jose del Monte City in Bulacan Province, on the east by San Mateo and Marikina, on the south by Pasig and Mandaluyong, San Juan and Manila, and on the west by Valenzuela, Caloocan, and Manila. Its northeastern and eastern boundaries are defined by the Novaliches Watershed and the Marikina River. With an area of 16,112.58 hectares (based on 1995 GIS graphical plot), it is the largest among the sixteen (16) cities and one (1) municipality in the region and is almost one-fourth the size of Metro Manila.

• Photofun photo albums

THE STORY OF THE HALLMARK BRAND AND FILSTAR, THE COMPANY, IN THE PHILIPPINES

The beginnings of Hallmark in the Philippines had its share of twists and charm. In 1969, people from Kansas City, U.S.A., home of the Hallmark headquarters, came to the Philippines looking for a local licensee. It was in National Book Store (NBS) that Hallmark discovered the qualities they too valued: the premium placed on excellence and the right attitude towards growth. These were the same qualities which the founder of NBS, Mrs. Socorro C. Ramos, valued.

It was a Good Friday when Mrs. Ramos was approached by Hallmark U.S.A. Thereafter, she went to Kansas City to arrange the deal and successfully came back with the license to manufacture and distribute Hallmark in the Philippines. It was on her kitchen table that the very first cards were planned. This was in 1973, the start of the Hallmark- NBS partnership. The next year, Hallmark cards made their appearance on the racks of National Book Store.

What followed were years of astounding growth and excellence. In product lines, from Christmas to everyday themes, more greeting cards and other excellent products have been added on each year to establish a full line of quality Hallmark merchandise.

Today, Filstar distributes to 1,000 outlets nationwide and has evolved to be a distributor of not just Hallmark, but of other products that supplement and enhance the personal expressions industry. The successful introduction of the All About Scrapbooking brand spearheaded the art of scrapbooking in the Philippines. It is now the top of mind brand of scrapbooking enthusiasts and hobbyists.		 22812 Retail Industry https://rec-data.kalibrr.com/logos/HE3KW56HQ9WRQHMYHZ4Y-5a2118fe.png Filstar Distributors Corporation true true filstar-distributors-corporation Filstar Distributors Corporation maintains the prestige of being the exclusive licensee of Hallmark Cards in the Philippines since 1974. • Celebration Balloons

• Photofun photo albums

THE STORY OF THE HALLMARK BRAND AND FILSTAR, THE COMPANY, IN THE PHILIPPINES

The beginnings of Hallmark in the Philippines had its share of twists and charm. In 1969, people from Kansas City, U.S.A., home of the Hallmark headquarters, came to the Philippines looking for a local licensee. It was in National Book Store (NBS) that Hallmark discovered the qualities they too valued: the premium placed on excellence and the right attitude towards growth. These were the same qualities which the founder of NBS, Mrs. Socorro C. Ramos, valued.

It was a Good Friday when Mrs. Ramos was approached by Hallmark U.S.A. Thereafter, she went to Kansas City to arrange the deal and successfully came back with the license to manufacture and distribute Hallmark in the Philippines. It was on her kitchen table that the very first cards were planned. This was in 1973, the start of the Hallmark- NBS partnership. The next year, Hallmark cards made their appearance on the racks of National Book Store.

What followed were years of astounding growth and excellence. In product lines, from Christmas to everyday themes, more greeting cards and other excellent products have been added on each year to establish a full line of quality Hallmark merchandise.

Today, Filstar distributes to 1,000 outlets nationwide and has evolved to be a distributor of not just Hallmark, but of other products that supplement and enhance the personal expressions industry. The successful introduction of the All About Scrapbooking brand spearheaded the art of scrapbooking in the Philippines. It is now the top of mind brand of scrapbooking enthusiasts and hobbyists.		 22812 Retail Industry https://rec-data.kalibrr.com/logos/HE3KW56HQ9WRQHMYHZ4Y-5a2118fe.png Filstar Distributors Corporation true true filstar-distributors-corporation Filstar Distributors Corporation maintains the prestige of being the exclusive licensee of Hallmark Cards in the Philippines since 1974. It now serves as the Philippines’ government center with the legislature and other important government offices located in its area. All of these are reminiscent of the same noble dream that brought forth the creation of the City.

Quezon City is situated on the northeast portion of Metro Manila. It is bounded on the north by Caloocan City and San Jose del Monte City in Bulacan Province, on the east by San Mateo and Marikina, on the south by Pasig and Mandaluyong, San Juan and Manila, and on the west by Valenzuela, Caloocan, and Manila. Its northeastern and eastern boundaries are defined by the Novaliches Watershed and the Marikina River. With an area of 16,112.58 hectares (based on 1995 GIS graphical plot), it is the largest among the sixteen (16) cities and one (1) municipality in the region and is almost one-fourth the size of Metro Manila.

VISION

The Quezon City Government envisions itself to be a model of effective governance and responsible leadership, working in partnership with the citizenry in building a Quality Community.

MISSION

And, beginning this year, APAC Business Insights recognized Cobena to be among Asia Pacific’s Fastest Growing Data analytics companies. Both publications are based in Silicon Valley.

Cobena has offices in the Philippines and Singapore.

Cobena in August 2020, became part of Demand Sciences, a business intelligence platform based in Boston Massachusetts.

<p>The Account Receivable Analyst is primarily responsible for effectively managing account receivables of the company and ensures that these are well-monitored and updated regularly. He/she needs to ensure that all credit policies are complied with.</p>

<p>Key Job Results include accurate, reliable, detailed and timely updating of account balances as well as professional growth of staff. As needed, provides customer assistance related to accounts reconciliation.</p>

<p><strong>Duties and Responsibilities:</strong></p>

<p><strong>Planning</strong></p>

<p>1. Works with the Immediate Superior in preparing new A/R policies and procedures.</p>

<p><strong>Doing/Execution </strong></p>

<p>2. Provides weekly Total AR report of handled accounts</p>

<p>3. Updates Account Balances in the SAP System.</p>

<p>3.1. Record/Clear payments to specific invoices.</p>

<p>3.2. Record/Clear validated returns and customer deductions.</p>

<p>4. Creates and Summarizes Unauthorized Customer Deductions and Returns Report.</p>

<p>5. Presents and explains new or revised A/R policies to concerned personnel.</p>

<p><strong>Checking/Monitoring</strong></p>

<p>6. Monitors Overdue Accounts</p>

<p>6.1 Provides updates to Sales Representative and/or client with their outstanding balances.</p>

<p>6.2 Works with Sales Representative in clearing or following up client’s overdue account.</p>

<p>6.2.1 Prepares letter for short payments and overdue accounts.</p>

<p>6.3 Prepares statement of accounts as requested by the customer or sales representative.</p>

<p>7. Checks and Validates Customer Returns and Deductions.</p>

<p>7.1 Coordination with concerned departments in validating customer deductions.</p>

<p>7.1.1 Checks returns deducted from the payment and validate its accuracy with the Warehouse Team.</p>

<p>7.2 Investigates client’s service level penalty.</p>

<p>8. Checks accuracy of Expanded Withholding Tax (EWT) computation.</p>

<p>8.1 Ensures that EWT computations are correct and must have a corresponding EWT certificate submitted by the customer.</p>

<p><strong>Acting/Adjusting </strong></p>

<p>9. Provides reliable, timely management reports on accounts receivables.</p>

<p>10. Works with A/R Supervisor and AVP-SSG in reviewing and revising existing A/R policies and procedures.</p>

<p>11. Recommends solutions in addressing unauthorized returns and deductions by the customer.</p>

<p>12. Prepares letter for add-back on unauthorized deductions.</p>

In 2006, Ramesh Trading changed its business type to Corporation as part of its efforts to improve itself in the new millennium coupled with the entry of the 3rd Generation now handling the business. After over 70 years of its existence, the company has successfully branched out its endeavors into importing, wholesaling and distributorship. In 2014, the Corporation moved to a bigger facility located in Pasay City which is in line with its expansion efforts. This will further improve the company's overall efficiency and effectiveness ratings and speed up its operations.

SKYdirect, now in over one million homes nationwide, brings SKY’s superior brand of cable entertainment options to more areas, beyond the urban centers via direct-to-home television technology.

THE STORY OF THE HALLMARK BRAND AND FILSTAR, THE COMPANY, IN THE PHILIPPINES

The beginnings of Hallmark in the Philippines had its share of twists and charm. In 1969, people from Kansas City, U.S.A., home of the Hallmark headquarters, came to the Philippines looking for a local licensee. It was in National Book Store (NBS) that Hallmark discovered the qualities they too valued: the premium placed on excellence and the right attitude towards growth. These were the same qualities which the founder of NBS, Mrs. Socorro C. Ramos, valued.

It was a Good Friday when Mrs. Ramos was approached by Hallmark U.S.A. Thereafter, she went to Kansas City to arrange the deal and successfully came back with the license to manufacture and distribute Hallmark in the Philippines. It was on her kitchen table that the very first cards were planned. This was in 1973, the start of the Hallmark- NBS partnership. The next year, Hallmark cards made their appearance on the racks of National Book Store.

What followed were years of astounding growth and excellence. In product lines, from Christmas to everyday themes, more greeting cards and other excellent products have been added on each year to establish a full line of quality Hallmark merchandise.

Today, Filstar distributes to 1,000 outlets nationwide and has evolved to be a distributor of not just Hallmark, but of other products that supplement and enhance the personal expressions industry. The successful introduction of the All About Scrapbooking brand spearheaded the art of scrapbooking in the Philippines. It is now the top of mind brand of scrapbooking enthusiasts and hobbyists.		 22812 Retail Industry https://rec-data.kalibrr.com/logos/HE3KW56HQ9WRQHMYHZ4Y-5a2118fe.png Filstar Distributors Corporation true true filstar-distributors-corporation Filstar Distributors Corporation maintains the prestige of being the exclusive licensee of Hallmark Cards in the Philippines since 1974. In addition, it was made the authorized distributor of the following brands:

• Pioneer Balloons from the U.S.A. in 1995
• BIC Stationery products from France in 2001; BIC Lighters and Shavers (exclusive distributorship)
• Everts Balloons from Malaysia in 2003
• Martha Stewart Crafts
• Scentco
• Disney Art Attack in 2012 (Licensee)
• Crayola (Licensee)

The company was the first to introduce the scrapbooking hobby in the Philippines, creating the brand Craft Easy, formerly known as All About Scrapbooking.

Other of its locally-created brands include:

• Celebration Balloons
• Wrapsody - a line of high-end quality gift wrap paper with special effects
• Wrap 'Em Up – ribbons and quick gift wrapping ideas
• Photofun photo albums

<ul>
<li>Coordinating efforts for their personal and professional growth in the organization</li>
<li>Creating opportunities for program participants and Staff to understand their growth and change</li>
<li>Equipping them to strengthen and share the same skills with the people they serve (students, co-teachers, etc.); and,</li>
<li>Allowing the Fellows and Staff to reflect on what is happening to them and consider alternative ways of doing things.</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>What processes does the job support?</strong> The Training Manager for Human Development works in a highly confidential setting and listens attentively at all times. The HDM is also a non-denominational role and is not about morals or values training nor is the HDM there to dispense advice, but rather help Fellows and Staff to make their own choices. The role requires consultation and direction from the Director of Program and Training.</p>

<p><strong>Why is the job important?</strong> The Training Manager for Human Development listens, analyzes, acts and reviews the Fellows' concerns, and in the process, promotes their leadership development. First, the role provides the space for Fellows to express their feelings, concerns, issues and questions, all in the effort for greater consciousness, understanding and clarity. Second, the HDM analyzes the patterns and trends, and thinks of how best to address and accomplish both leadership and human development. Third, actions are taken, whether as training given, organizational suggestions, or continued conversations. Lastly, a review is done in order to see the effect of the changes instituted.</p>

<p><strong>What position does this job report to?</strong> This role reports to the Director for Programs and Training, with additional coordination with the Chief Programs Officer, and to a certain extent, with the Instructional Coaching Director and Coaches.</p>

<p><strong>What is the span of control of the role?</strong> The Training Manager for Human Development proactively schedules with Fellows either for individual or group colloquia. Aside from the scheduled colloquia, Fellows may have individual colloquia, either through their own scheduling or through the suggestion of their manager. For projects, trainings and programs, this may be given by the executives or directors, or this may be proactively suggested to them.</p>

<p><strong>What are the main challenges facing this role? </strong>This role needs a mature person who has a high level of empathy for all the characters involved, and is able to practice detachment and self-care. The Training Manager for Human Development needs to be able to listen and ask meaningful questions that provoke thoughtful realizations and solutions. The Training Manager for Human Development likewise needs to analyze meta-data in order to give suggestions for the continued leadership and human development of Fellows.</p>		 550 false 2020-11-09T09:40:50.691487+00:00 Public Service and NGOs Paseo de Roxas Makati Philippines Metro Manila 162893 false false Training Manager for Human Development 1 1 <p><u><strong>Knowledge</strong></u></p>

<li>Assists in designing various processes including organizational charts and process flow to understand and document the work of the unit.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Comes up with an initial analysis based on data gathered from the unit, its stakeholders, and other relevant sources.</li>
<li>Assists in designing organization development (OD) interventions and evaluation processes to address gaps determined in the organizational diagnosis phase. </li>
<li>Carries out OD interventions and initiatives (i.e. competency development, systems review and improvement, change management, succession planning, process re-engineering, etc.) as assigned by the Organization Capability and Succession Section Head.
<ul>
<li>Assists in monitoring, coordinating, implementing, and evaluating organization development projects, keeping track of the deliverables, timelines, and agreements</li>
<li>(Co)Facilitates individual and group discussions, and workshops towards the achievement of the required process.</li>
<li>Proposes action points and process improvements, based on what is applicable and realistic given the unit’s context.</li>
<li>Assists the Workforce Strategy &amp; Branding (WSB) Section and the Career &amp; Learning Development (CLD) in carrying out needed interventions.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>II. Organization and Job Design</strong></p>

<ul>
<li>Assists in reviewing the effectiveness of an organizational unit, proposing job designs, processes, and systems that can bring about optimal results for the unit to achieve its mandates, based on the inputs gathered from its stakeholders and data from industry practices. </li>
<li>Works with the Workforce Strategy and Branding Section in ensuring that all job levels accurately reflect the worth of the jobs, that proper classification and nomenclatures are followed.</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>III. Talent Development and Succession</strong></p>

<ul>
<li>Researches on talent development and succession systems within and among the academic community and other industries.</li>
<li>Benchmarks best practices in employee learning and development that cover frameworks, assessment strategies, development of interventions, implementation, and evaluation systems.</li>
<li>Assists in monitoring qualification standards and competencies for different job families and job classification.
<ul>
<li>Assists in identifying and developing talent identification criteria.</li>
<li>Assists in the design (review and update) of talent development and succession systems and interventions.</li>
<li>Assists in the conduct and evaluation of the talent development programs.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Assists in communicating and marketing the University’s talent development and succession program to unit heads and employees.
<ul>
<li>Monitors talent development and succession planning initiatives and projects and provides updates on a monthly basis on the status of such initiatives.</li>
<li>Assists in driving a culture that supports continuous improvement in talent development and succession.</li>
<li>Monitors employee profiles and capability development with the Career and Learning Development Section, tracking employees with the potential to take on leadership positions.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Conducts data gathering and consultations with key stakeholders in the design of learning programs for talents and leaders.
<ul>
<li>Coordinates the development of systematic learning interventions that are aligned with the organization’s and balanced with the individual needs.</li>
<li>Assists in coordinating, organizing, and evaluating the talent development and succession programs for potential and incumbent leaders, and unit administrators.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>

<p>IV. <strong>OHRMOD-Specific</strong>: <strong>Quality Review</strong></p>

<ul>
<li>Assists in reviewing OHRMOD’s processes, systems, and practices to ensure operational efficiency and effective delivery of services.</li>
<li>Assists in monitoring the achievement of OHRMOD’s goals.</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>V. HR Partnering</strong></p>

<ul>
<li>Keeps track of updates and developments that affect the University as an organization, including its employees.</li>
<li>Keeps abreast of trends and changes happening in the University and with the client.</li>
<li>Manages and maintains relationships with clients.</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>VI. Administrative Functions</strong></p>

<ul>
<li>Assists in monitoring, coordinating, implementing, and evaluating all the Section’s projects, keeping track of the deliverables, timelines, agreements, including possible sustainability measures.
<ul>
<li>Ensures all accountabilities are delivered, including payments to suppliers and contractors.</li>
<li>Recommends improvements in the Section’s systems, processes, and programs.</li>
<li>Assists in budgeting for the Section’s operational requirements.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Assists in communicating the programs of the Section to unit heads and employees.</li>
<li>Manages and keeps the project team abreast of developments, when necessary.</li>
<li>Oversees the coordination, logistical, and resource requirements of the Section’s projects and activities.</li>
<li>Documents all meetings, proceedings, and events of the Section’s projects and activities.</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>VII. Performs all other duties as may be reasonably required of the position, in accordance with the instructions of the Immediate Supervisor, and it's duly authorized representative.</strong></p>		 550 false 2020-11-09T05:17:43.814462+00:00 Human Resources Katipunan Loyola Heights Quezon City Philippines Metro Manila 163807 false false HR Officer | Organization Capability and Succession Section 1 1 <p><strong>Education and Experience Requirements</strong> </p>
